Vice President Mike Pence visited West Point to join the United States Corps of Cadets and give thanks on behalf of President Donald Trump. Pence participated in a roundtable discussion with African-American cadets and gave remarks at the 40th annual Henry O. Flipper dinner. He honored the history of African-Americans serving in the military, including the first African-American graduate of West Point, Henry Flipper, and others such as the Buffalo Soldiers and the Tuskegee Airmen. Pence highlighted the importance of the military's service in a world filled with conflict and chaos and expressed his and Trump's commitment to supporting the armed forces. He praised the courage, selflessness, and patriotism displayed by the cadets and expressed optimism about America's future.